<font color="#FF0000">MY EXPERIENCE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 11  3:37:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
As I said, I do have quite a bit to say about the subject of religion in Vietnam.  I feel that I survived my Air Force experience, and the war, because I held true to my convictions that<br><br>
--We are responsible for our actions.<br><br>
--We have to live with the consequences of what we do, individually and collectively, as we go through life.<br><br>
--That some of these consequences of our individual and our collective actions deal with keeping ourselves healthy, staying out of harm's way, and living a life (even in uniform, or maybe, especially when in uniform) we can look back upon without regrets.  <br><br>
How did this square with my Vietnam experience?  I came form a liturgical church, the Episcopal Church of America.  I studied the Bible while in the service, and tried to live my life in accordance to the Great Commandment to &quot;Love God with all our hearts, minds and soul, and love our neighbor as ourselves.&quot;  I got quite a bit of flack for not drinking, not roving with the boys to the taverns and brothels of Asia, and staying away from situations which I felt would compromise my own values.  <br><br>
Part of the reason why I did this was because I was the God Father of a boy who had grown up in an orphanage in Korea until he was adopted by an Oregon family through the Holt Adoption Program.  In my high school days, I not only got to know him and his family very well, but also got to know the Holt family very well.  I visited them in Korea too, where the Holt Adoption Program maintained an orphanage near Seoul.  <br><br>
These experiences gave me a &quot;different&quot; outlook on immoral behavior from my fellow servicemen.  I knew the consequences of their behavior, in broken lives, in impoverished children who were sometimes given away by their mothers because their mothers had no means of supporting them once the serviceman they had hoped to marry moved away, back to the States, to the &quot;Land of Round-eyes.&quot;  I had seen one of these women attempt suicide in Korea after her boyfriend DEROSed .  In other words, war or no war, I knew what happened afterward, as it had already happened in Korea.<br><br>
My moral convictions were already well set when I decided to volunteer for Vietnam.  But that decision was marked by, well...indecision.  I did not have to go.  My parents did not want me to go.  I could get out of the service having fulfilled my obligation, without having gone to Vietnam.  But the Vietnam experience beckoned.  Why?  Why the pull to go there?  <br><br>
I had volunteered for rescue work, and had done 3 and a half years.  I could re-up, decide to become a lifer, and potentially go to Vietnam.  Or I could get out and go back to school.  Or, and this is what I did, I could volunteer to go to Vietnam, then get out and go back to school.  I actually rigged it so that I could get an early out off the extension of my enlistment.<br><br>
Unlike most who went to Vietnam, I picked the base I wanted to go to and the unit, the 37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron.  I essentially picked the mission, which was out-of-country combat rescue.  <br><br>
One of the questions asked was how, when both sides claim to be fighting for God, one side could claim to be in better status with God.  This assumes several things, the first being a monotheism, and that each side believed the same.  Unfortunately, in essence neither side thought that way.  <br><br>
On the communist side, they disavowed any relationship with any god, other than the &quot;state.&quot;  They persecuted those with differing beliefs unmercifully.  One only needs to read accounts of the communists tactics in Dr. Tom Dooley's &quot;The Night They Burned The Mountain&quot; to see what happened to those who went against them.  Another book, a historical novel I referred to this time last year, is John M. Del Vecchio's &quot;For The Sake Of All Living Things.&quot;  This book gives detail in a way only a historical novel can to the tactics used in North Vietnam, Laos , Cambodia, and South Vietnam by the communists.  The tactics that the communists used on the populations would qualify as &quot;terrorist&quot; activities in today's language.<br><br>
But when we examine our side, the American and South Vietnamese side of the war, we find something that I found downright frightening.  There was no moral imperative, no striving to win, no esprit-de-corps on the part of many units.  (I know that there were notable exceptions to this assessment; I am speaking of the leadership, both ours and theirs in South Vietnam.) The leadership simply was not there.  Without establishing a moral imperative, servicemen felt free to do what needed (they felt) to be done to survive.  Therefore, conduct was largely left to the individual.  <br><br>
Those who entered the war without a very finely tuned sense of personal convictions had a very rough time of it, trying to define themselves while everything was happening around them.  Those who had personal convictions had them severely tested during this process.  The ones who made it through, by and large, came out stronger.  Those who did not sometimes came out broken.  If they weren't broken getting out, the shock of the trip home, and homecoming itself, did in many people.   <br><br>
One of my guiding principals was a passage from The Letter from James in the New Testament.  It reads &quot;Does anyone think he is religious? If he does not control his tongue, his religion is worthless and he deceives himself.  What God the Father considers to be pure and genuine religion is this: to take care of orphans and widows in their suffering and to keep oneself from being corrupted by the world.&quot;  (James, 1:26-27)<br><br>
St. John also wrote, <br><br>
&quot;The message you heard from the very beginning is this: we must love one another.  We must not be like Cain; he belonged to the Evil One and murdered his own brother Abel.  Why did Cain murder him?  Because the things he himself did were wrong, and the things his brother did were right.  <br><br>
&quot;So do not be surprised, my brothers, if the people of the world hate you.  We know that we have left death and come over into life; we know it because we love our brothers.  Whoever does not love is still under the power of death.  Whoever hates his brother is o murderer, and you know that a murderer does not have eternal life in him.  This is how we know what love is: Christ gave his life for us.  We too, then, ought to give our lives for our brothers! If a rich person sees his brother in need, yet closes his heart against his brother, how can he claim that he loves God?  My children, our love should not be just words and talk; it must be true love, which shows itself in action.&quot;  (1 John 3:11-17)<br><br>
These two passages set my way of thinking while in Vietnam.  I was there on a rescue mission; combat, yes...hate, no.  Once one of the other PJ's asked me whether, if on a rescue mission deep in enemy territory I came across the enemy incapacitated and unconscious, I would kill him.  I said no, I would not.  I would be like the Indian who came with a light foot, and left without a trace and without knowledge of the enemy that I had passed.  That was not my mission.<br><br>
I could kill, and manned the miniguns when that was necessary.  But that was because it was an act of self-defense.  Rescue was not offensive work, but trying to pick up the pieces after an attack.  <br><br>
PJ's were respected by the enemy.  There was one story of a rescue where the pilot on the ground had an injury, and the PJ had come down the helicopter hoist to locate him.  As he attended the wounds of the pilot, NVA were close enough to flick cigarette butts down on them.  They called the helicopter, and told them the situation.  The helicopter crew elected to attempt the rescue anyway.  They came in and lowered the hoist.  The PJ put the pilot into the jungle penetrator, seated himself in it, and called for an &quot;Up hoist!&quot;  The NVA waited until they started up to fire, but not at them, at the helicopter in an attempt to down the chopper.  The chopper waited until they were a bit higher in the trees, then took off after suffering many hits (the PJ said it was raining JP-4 and hydraulic fluid).  The helicopter dragged them through the trees as it began the takeoff, and they had their clothes torn to shreds (not to mention their bodies).  They all made it out.  The NVA would not shoot at them, dangling from the hoist cable!<br><br>
There was a lot of God's intervention for me too, at least it seemed so to me.  The war seemed to slow down while I was there.  I wasn't involved in many missions, and the rocket attacks seemed slower than at times just before and after I was there.  I cannot explain this.  <br><br>
I can say that I had help in the form of audio tapes of our priest's talks. Father Daniel Ferry from St. Paul's Episcopal Church in Salem, Oregon explained his teachings in such a way that it was easy to understand, and it had meaning even to me, half-way around the world in the middle of a war.  <br><br>
Because of my teachings, I do not classify according to labels.  I have seen too many &quot;Christians&quot; who do not act from love.  I once turned off the volume of a fundamentalist Christian preacher on television, and asked my very young sons about the person on the screen.  Was he happy, mad, loving, kind, hateful?  They answered that he was mad, and seemed to hate people.  This came from 4- and 6-year-olds.  If you watch a TV preacher, turn off the volume and see what body language he or she is speaking.  Educators say that up to 75% of a message comes from how we say things, not what we say.  Think about it.<br><br>
I think, therefore, that Mahatma Ghandi was as great a Christian as was the Rev. Martin Luther King.  He expressed love for all people, and left it to others to judge people.  <br><br>
My religion was formulated in the crucible of the Vietnam War.  It is therefore very difficult for any other experience to penetrate through and change.  It is not impossible, but it is difficult.  <br><br>
If I can leave one message to others, perhaps reading this site, it is to love one another, even if someone calls him or her an enemy.  <br><br>
This is why, just a few weeks ago I was able to state on one of these threads that we love Doc Spatz, but dislike immensely his behavior.  Some may choose not to agree with this, but this manner of reacting to this situation also flows from my Vietnam experience.  If I did not hate the enemy there, how could I hate Spatz?  I cannot and will not.  If he shows up at my home, he will be invited in for coffee, the same an any of the rest of you.  <br><br>
As I write these words, I have been watching segments of &quot;Dances With Wolves.&quot;  The US Military is not and never has been completely correct is all its doings.  I do not condone some of the actions during our Indian wars, and I do not condone some of our actions during Vietnam (the Calley massacre is quite notable here).  But each person must decide these things for him- or herself.  <br><br>
We must all take responsibility for own actions, and not let others dictate them.  It is very possible to serve with distinction, and serve in war.  It is also very possible to be called upon and not be there, or get out of our responsibilities.  <br><br>
Class Lass, I hope this answers some of your questions for this thread.<br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


